---
import BlogLayout from '../../layouts/BlogLayout.astro';

const faqs = [
  { q: 'Are the generated passwords truly random?', a: 'Yes. The tool uses crypto.getRandomValues() — the browser\'s cryptographically secure random number generator, the same used in TLS and encryption libraries. It is not based on Math.random().' },
  { q: 'What length should my password be?', a: 'For most accounts, 16 characters with mixed character sets gives over 90 bits of entropy — considered very secure. For servers and databases, use 24+ characters.' },
  { q: 'Is it safe to use this tool for real passwords?', a: 'Yes. Everything runs in your browser — no passwords are sent to any server. After generating, copy and store it in a password manager like Bitwarden or 1Password.' },
  { q: 'What are ambiguous characters?', a: 'Characters like 0 (zero), O (capital O), l (lowercase L), 1 (one), and I (capital i) look similar in many fonts. Excluding them prevents transcription errors when you type the password manually.' },
];
---

<BlogLayout
  title="How to Generate a Strong Password Online for Free"
  description="Generate a cryptographically secure random password online for free. Set length, choose character sets, exclude ambiguous characters. Instant, browser-based."
  canonical="/blog/how-to-generate-strong-password-online-free"
  date="2026-06-30"
  readTime="4 min read"
  category="Developer Tools"
  faqs={faqs}
>
  <p>Using weak passwords is one of the top causes of account breaches. Using the same password on multiple sites is nearly as bad. A strong, unique password for every account is the baseline — and generating one manually is impractical.</p>

  <h2>How to Generate a Strong Password</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Go to <a href="https://textwonder.com/devwonder/password-generator">textwonder.com/devwonder/password-generator</a></li>
    <li>Set the password length using the slider (4–128 characters). 16+ is recommended.</li>
    <li>Choose which character sets to include: uppercase, lowercase, numbers, symbols.</li>
    <li>Optionally check "Exclude ambiguous characters" to avoid 0, O, l, 1, I.</li>
    <li>Click <strong>Generate Password</strong>. The strength meter shows entropy in bits.</li>
    <li>Click <strong>Copy</strong> and paste it into your password manager.</li>
    <li>Use <strong>Generate 10</strong> to get a batch of 10 passwords — click any to copy.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Understanding the Strength Meter</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Weak</strong> (under 40 bits) — Crackable in seconds with modern hardware</li>
    <li><strong>Fair</strong> (40–60 bits) — Adequate for low-stakes accounts</li>
    <li><strong>Strong</strong> (60–80 bits) — Good for most personal accounts</li>
    <li><strong>Very Strong</strong> (80+ bits) — Required for servers, databases, and admin accounts</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What to Do With a Generated Password</h2>
  <p>Never write passwords in a text file or email. Use a password manager: <strong>Bitwarden</strong> (free, open-source), <strong>1Password</strong>, or your browser's built-in password manager. The password manager stores the password securely so you only need to remember one master password.</p>

  <div class="my-8 p-5 bg-cyan-950/30 border border-cyan-700/40 rounded-xl text-center">
    <p class="text-white font-semibold mb-2">Generate a Strong Password Free</p>
